  "prompt": "What are the incarnations of lord Krishna in kaliyuga?",
  "response": "In Hinduism, Lord Krishna is considered a complete incarnation (or avatar) of Vishnu. While the more widely known incarnations or avatars of Vishnu include the Dashavatara (the ten principal avatars), there are beliefs regarding the future appearances of Krishna in the current age, Kaliyuga.\n\nIn Kaliyuga, it is believed that Lord Krishna will have various forms or manifestations. Two significant forms often mentioned are:\n\n1. **Kalki Avatar**: This is considered the future incarnation of Vishnu, who is expected to appear in the Kaliyuga to restore dharma (righteousness) and destroy adharma (unrighteousness). Kalki is prophesied to come riding a white horse, wielding a sword, to bring an end to the current age of chaos and corruption.\n\n2. **Krishna in Yugas**: While Krishna primarily manifested during the Dvapara Yuga, he is considered timeless and omnipresent. His principles, teachings, and divine play (lila) are believed to remain influential and guiding even in Kaliyuga.\n\nIt is worth noting that interpretations and beliefs may vary among different sects and communities within Hinduism regarding the nature and timing of these manifestations.",
